body:
Merge group definitions referencing the same group declaration. This should likely be a separate pass that runs right before `GroupSink`.

Consider the following:

```
FIRRTL version 3.2.0
circuit Foo: %[[
  {"class":"firrtl.transforms.DontTouchAnnotation", "target":"~Foo|Foo>A_a"},
  {"class":"firrtl.transforms.DontTouchAnnotation", "target":"~Foo|Foo>A_b"}
]]
  declgroup A, bind:

  module Foo:
    input a: UInt<1>
    input b: UInt<1>

    group A:
      node A_a = a

    group A:
      node A_b = b
```

Currently this compiles to:

```verilog
// Generated by CIRCT firtool-1.56.1-64-gfac210553
module Foo_A(
  input _a
);

  wire A_a = _a;
endmodule

module Foo_A_0(
  input _b
);

  wire A_b = _b;
endmodule

module Foo(
  input a,
        b
);

endmodule

// ----- 8< ----- FILE "groups_Foo_A.sv" ----- 8< -----

// Generated by CIRCT firtool-1.56.1-64-gfac210553
`ifndef groups_Foo_A
`define groups_Foo_A
bind Foo Foo_A foo_A (
  ._a (a)
);
bind Foo Foo_A_0 foo_A_0 (
  ._b (b)
);
`endif // groups_Foo_A
```

However, the two modules bound into `Foo`, `Foo_A`, and `Foo_A_0` (originating from the two group definitions) can be combined into one.

Note that there is nothing invalid about the current emission per the FIRRTL ABI! This has some benefit as it enables more work for `GroupSink` as common code shared between the two split group definitions can now be sunk.
